# ISS Contamination Crisis — Mission Control Agent Definitions

## Scenario Briefing (shared context for all agents)

**Date:** March 2026
**Situation:** The International Space Station has been contaminated by a substance that absolutely cannot be allowed to enter Earth’s atmosphere in any form — not as intact structure, not as debris, not as vaporized particles during reentry. 100% of the station is compromised. The ISS must be removed from Earth orbit and reach Earth escape velocity (or a solution of equivalent safety) with its structural integrity substantially preserved. Breakup during the operation is a mission failure equivalent to atmospheric reentry.

**Key Physical Constraints (all agents must internalize these):**

- ISS mass: ~420,000 kg (420 metric tons)
- Current orbit: ~408 km altitude, 51.6° inclination, orbital velocity ~7.66 km/s
- Delta-v for trans-lunar injection from LEO: ~3.1 km/s
- Delta-v for Earth escape from LEO: ~3.2 km/s
- Delta-v for high graveyard orbit (above GEO, ~36,000 km): ~2.4 km/s
- Tsiolkovsky rocket equation: Δv = Isp × g₀ × ln(m_initial / m_final)
- At Isp 450s (high-performance hydrolox): escaping Earth requires mass ratio ~2.05, meaning ~440 tons of propellant for the ISS alone
- At Isp 350s (kerolox, e.g. Raptor methane): mass ratio ~2.55, meaning ~650+ tons of propellant
- ISS maximum demonstrated reboost acceleration: ~0.01 m/s² (Zvezda module thrusters)
- ISS structural load limits: the truss and solar arrays were designed for microgravity assembly; sustained thrust loads above ~0.02–0.05 m/s² risk structural failure at truss joints and SARJ (Solar Alpha Rotary Joint) bearings
- Atmospheric drag at 408 km causes ~2 km/month orbital decay; without reboosts, uncontrolled reentry in roughly 1–2 years depending on solar activity
- Current global annual launch capacity to LEO (all providers, surge): ~300–500 metric tons, heavily dependent on Starship operational status

**Available Launch Vehicles (2026 estimates):**

|Vehicle                    |Payload to LEO       |Status             |Notes                                                |
|---------------------------|---------------------|-------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
|SpaceX Starship/Super Heavy|~100–150 tons        |Operational (early)|Highest single-launch capacity; reusable; methane/LOX|
|SpaceX Falcon Heavy        |~63 tons (expendable)|Operational        |Proven but expensive in expendable mode              |
|SpaceX Falcon 9            |~22.8 tons           |Operational        |Workhorse, high cadence                              |
|ULA Vulcan Centaur         |~27 tons             |Operational        |Hydrolox upper stage, high Isp                       |
|Arianespace Ariane 6       |~21.6 tons (A64)     |Operational        |ESA primary launcher                                 |
|JAXA H3                    |~6.5 tons            |Operational        |Limited capacity                                     |
|Roscosmos Proton-M         |~23 tons             |Operational        |Russian heavy lift                                   |
|Roscosmos Angara A5        |~24.5 tons           |Operational        |Newer Russian heavy                                  |
|CNSA Long March 5          |~25 tons             |Operational        |Chinese heavy lift                                   |
|CNSA Long March 9          |~150 tons            |In development     |May not be available                                 |

**Communication Protocol:** All agents communicate through shared Letta channels. The Flight Director is the coordination authority. All major proposals must be reviewed by the Referee before adoption. Agents should challenge each other’s assumptions, request specifics, and refuse to accept hand-waving. Every plan element must have numbers attached.

